267<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 11:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=922.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There was a way to launch a sattalite by the year 1910</span><hr size=1> This time I think you've understated the case, if anything, and you may have the seeds of a very interesting alternate history here.<br>
The rocket equation was well-understood by 1910 and good public relations could have made it more so. Aluminum was available for structural use by then, and fairly well understood, since the Hall-Heroult process had been invented in 1889. <br>
I think 1910 vintage radio was probably advanced enough for space use; it had already been used from airships by then, and the first airplane installation followed in 1911 or so, iirc. Trans-Atlantic broadcasts had been made as early as 1901. Even the rocket turbo-pump was not entirely out of reach, since steam turbines had been around since the mid-1890s and hydrogen peroxide decomposition was well understood, if very dangerous. <br>
I might be wrong, but I think that inhibited red fuming nitric acid (IRFNA) had been developed by 1910. If so, this would simplify the construction of the propellant tanks. <br>
A very good source for information on this kind of stuff is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Oxford History of Technology</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a comprehensive multi-volume set (8, iirc again) that covers all forms of technology from prehistoric times up to about 1960.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 12:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=922.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There was a way to launch a sattalite by the year 1910</span><hr size=1> <br>
Well, there has always been no doubt in my mind that a satellite could have been orbited well before 1957. I’m sure that if the leaders of the Third Reich had wanted to they could have got Von Braun and his group to launch a satellite sometime during WWII.<br>
What’s amazing to me is that during Operation Paperclip, in which German rocket scientists were sent to the States, we tried to teach them what <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>we</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> knew about rockets while they were already light-years ahead of us in this type of knowledge.<br>
If we would have let Von Braun go wild, I’m sure that he could have had something easily in orbit by 1950. <br>
Just the fact that we did nothing for years after the war in terms of trying to put things into orbit shows that we only stalled Von Braun's efforts.<br>
All we had was the Redstone which was really like a V-2 on steroids and was developed for the Army which didn’t fire things into space. <br>
I’ve always thought that 1957 was a little late for a satellite…<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 268<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 1:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=922.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There was a way to launch a sattalite by the year 1910</span><hr size=1> Von Braun's German contingent was not alone in advocating the feasibility of spaceflight years ahead of the actual event. Young Arthur C. Clarke and his colleagues at the British Interplanetary Society developed a very detailed plan for a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Launchpad/6133/moonlanding.html">moon rocket in 1939</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The British Interplanetary Society formed in Liverpool in 1933, and, due to a British law prohibiting the building of rockets by private individuals, concentrated on theoretical work in astronautics. In 1937 it was decided to begin as study of a Lunar landing mission, in order to prove that such missions were possible.<br>
The design created by the BIS was based on the most advanced technology then available: fairly small solid-fuel rockets developed by the army. The moon rocket, 30.5 meters high, 6.09 meters in diameter, and weighing 1000 tonnes, would use 2,490 solid-fuel rockets arranged in layers which fell away after use. This would be sufficient to allow the spacecraft to escape the Earth and begin its path to the moon.<br>
<br>
The astronauts themselves would fly in a pressure cabin/lander mounted on top of the rocket, which looked remarkably like a mixture of the Apollo Landing and Command Modules. The crew of three would lie in couches for the launch itself, protected from the friction of the air against the rocket by a heat shield, while filters removed water vapour and Carbon Dioxide from the cabin. At the end of the mission, the capsule would return its passengers to the Earth by bleeding off speed against the atmosphere and then parachuting to the ground.<br>
<br>
For the exploration of the moon itself, the three-man crew were to be provided with leather and rubber spacesuits designed by H.E. Ross. The suits included a radio, temperature control and an oxygen supply in a backpack, all features included in the Apollo suits 30 years later. The 1930s mission was very meticulously planned, with even the food supplies noted: bread, butter, cheese porridge and cocoa for energy. Coffee was included as an aid in the pre-computer age for &quot;Navigators falling asleep over their interminable calculations&quot;.<br>
<br>
The mission was redesigned by the BIS in 1949, to take account of the huge advances in rocketry brought on by the Second World War, most notably the V2. This mission used more efficient liquid fuel rather than solid rockets, and successfully predicted several features of the American landings of the 1960s.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
The main point of the exercise was that it could be built and flown with the available technology of the time. It is important to emphasize that the necessary solid fuel rockets existed at the time. The performance figures are certainly over-optimistic if we remember that Saturn V was over 3 times as large and had a much higher average isp, but the BIS rocket would probably have reached Earth orbit with a crewed vehicle as payload. Clarke and the rest of the committee obviously knew these limitations and we can speculate that they threw in the Moon landing goal as an attention getter, and as a showcase for their lunar exploration studies whose realization would have required a more powerful rocket.<br>
  <br>
The 1939 BIS moon rocket was an example of a cellular rocket, a type that uses a very large number of individual  rockets which are sequentially ignited to produce a kind of continuous staging. A German company, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/otrag.htm">OTRAG,</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> attempted to revive the cellular rocket idea in the 1970s (but with liquid fuel) but ran into political trouble. <br>
<br>
I ran across some very interesting resources on this proposal, including a photo of the Science Museum's <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/on-line/clarke/bisapoll.asp">model of the 1939 lunar lander</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> beside a same-scale model of the Apollo LM. <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.cix.co.uk/~sjbradshaw/baxterium/firstmoon.pdf">This one (a pdf file)</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is an alternate history of a moon landing in 1950 that takes off from the 1939 BIS proposal. <br>
<br>
The 1939 Moon rocket was no off the wall proposal. <br>
The BIS studied such things as control, navigation, and the lunar environment, designed a space suit, and even invented (and patented) an ingenious device (the &quot;caeleostat&quot;) for getting stationary views of the stars from a rotating spacecraft. <br>
According to David Baker's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Rocket</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the members of the design committee were H. Bramhill, Arthur C. Clarke, Val Cleaver, M. Hanson, Arthur Jansur, S. Klemantaski, H.E. Ross, R.A. Smith, and J. Happian Edwards. Much of the credit for the design goes to Ross, Smith, and Edwards.       <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 232<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 3:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=922.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There was a way to launch a sattalite by the year 1910</span><hr size=1> Calculations could have been performed using a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ex.ac.uk/BABBAGE/cbae.gif" target="top">Difference Engine</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> as designed by Charles Babbage.<br>
<br>
There is a whole genre of SF dedicated to Steam Tech/Victorian <br>
